I dont understand how you can say this is DNS server
ChatGPT said:
That‚Äôs a great question ‚Äî and you‚Äôre right to ask it.
Let‚Äôs carefully go step-by-step so you see exactly how this machine is functioning as a DNS server, not just that ‚Äúit works.‚Äù

üß† What Makes a System a DNS Server?
A DNS server (Domain Name System server) is a system that:

Listens on port 53 (UDP/TCP) for DNS queries.

Resolves domain names to IP addresses (and vice versa).

Optionally, forwards unknown queries to upstream DNS servers (like 8.8.8.8).

Publishes its own DNS zones ‚Äî meaning it‚Äôs the authority for specific domains.

Your setup with BIND9 satisfies all four points.

üîç 1. BIND9 Installed and Running as a DNS Service
You installed:

sudo apt install bind9 dnsutils bind9utils -y
and confirmed it‚Äôs running:

systemctl status bind9
‚Üí ‚úÖ active (running)

That means named (the BIND9 daemon) is actively listening on port 53.

You can verify:

sudo ss -lntup | grep named
Expected output:

udp   UNCONN  0 0 0.0.0.0:53   ...  named
tcp   LISTEN  0 0 0.0.0.0:53   ...  named
‚úîÔ∏è The machine is now a DNS service endpoint.

üó∫Ô∏è 2. It Hosts a Custom DNS Zone (Your Own Domain)
You defined:

zone "localdomain.lan" {
    type master;
    file "/etc/bind/zones/db.localdomain.lan";
};
and inside that file:

dns IN A 192.168.0.128
This makes your server the authoritative source for the domain localdomain.lan.
In other words:

Any computer that asks this server about dns.localdomain.lan gets the official answer from your configuration.

üîÅ 3. It Performs Reverse Lookups
You defined:

zone "0.168.192.in-addr.arpa" {
    type master;
    file "/etc/bind/zones/db.192.168.0";
};
and inside:

128 IN PTR dns.localdomain.lan.
Now the server can map an IP ‚Üí hostname.
That‚Äôs a key DNS function for networked environments.

üåê 4. It Forwards Internet DNS Queries
Your named.conf.options includes:

forwarders {
    8.8.8.8;
    8.8.4.4;
};
recursion yes;
So, if someone asks your DNS server about google.com,
and you‚Äôre not authoritative for it,
the query is automatically forwarded to Google‚Äôs public DNS ‚Äî
and the result is cached locally for faster future responses.

You tested that:

dig google.com @127.0.0.1
‚úÖ It returned a valid IP ‚Üí your BIND server successfully resolved an external domain.

üß© 5. It Answers Queries from Other Machines
In /etc/bind/named.conf.options you allowed:

allow-query { localhost; 192.168.0.0/24; };
That means any host in your LAN (192.168.0.x) can use this system‚Äôs IP (192.168.0.128) as its DNS server in /etc/resolv.conf or network settings.

Example from another client:

dig dns.localdomain.lan @192.168.0.128
‚úÖ You‚Äôll get the same reply, proving your machine is serving the network.

üß± 6. Summary: What You Have Built
Component	Purpose	Verified
BIND9 service	Core DNS daemon	‚úÖ running
Forward zone (localdomain.lan)	Resolves hostnames to IPs	‚úÖ works
Reverse zone	Resolves IPs to hostnames	‚úÖ configured
Forwarders	Sends external queries to Google DNS	‚úÖ works
Recursion	Caches and answers queries	‚úÖ yes
Access control	Limits to LAN + localhost	‚úÖ yes
Firewall rule	Allows DNS traffic	‚úÖ yes
‚úÖ Therefore, this machine is a fully functional DNS server ‚Äî both authoritative (for localdomain.lan) and recursive/forwarding (for the internet).

