‚ö†Ô∏è If it fails, your Windows machine and the VM are not in the same network ‚Äî
fix that first (see ‚ÄúTroubleshooting network‚Äù section below).

üß© Step 2: Temporarily Set Your Windows DNS Server
ü™ü Option 1: Through GUI
Open Control Panel ‚Üí Network and Internet ‚Üí Network and Sharing Center

Click Change adapter settings

Right-click your active network adapter ‚Üí Properties

Select Internet Protocol Version 4 (TCP/IPv4) ‚Üí click Properties

Choose ‚ÄúUse the following DNS server addresses‚Äù

Enter:

Preferred DNS server: 192.168.0.128
Alternate DNS server: 8.8.8.8   (optional backup)
Click OK ‚Üí OK

Now your Windows machine is using your VM‚Äôs BIND9 as its DNS resolver.

üß† Option 2: Command Line (Quick)
Run in Command Prompt (Run as Administrator):

netsh interface ip set dns "Ethernet" static 192.168.0.128
If you‚Äôre on Wi-Fi:

netsh interface ip set dns "Wi-Fi" static 192.168.0.128
To verify:

nslookup
> server
It should show:

Default Server:  dns.localdomain.lan
Address:  192.168.0.128
üß™ Step 3: Test Local Resolution
Now, test if Windows can resolve the DNS record you defined.

In Command Prompt:

nslookup dns.localdomain.lan
Expected output:

Server:  dns.localdomain.lan
Address: 192.168.0.128

Name:    dns.localdomain.lan
Address: 192.168.0.128
‚úÖ If you see that ‚Äî your Windows system is resolving through your BIND DNS!

üåç Step 4: Test Internet Forwarding
Still in Command Prompt:

nslookup google.com
Expected:

Server:  dns.localdomain.lan
Address: 192.168.0.128

Non-authoritative answer:
Name:    google.com
Address: 142.250.xx.xx
‚úÖ This means your DNS server is forwarding external queries properly to Google‚Äôs public DNS (as configured).

üîÅ Step 5: Restore Windows DNS (Optional)
If you just wanted to test temporarily, revert:

netsh interface ip set dns "Ethernet" dhcp
Or through GUI ‚Üí select ‚ÄúObtain DNS server address automatically.‚Äù

üß∞ Troubleshooting (If Ping/Lookup Fails)
Problem	Possible Cause	Fix
ping 192.168.0.128 fails	Different networks or VirtualBox NAT mode	Switch enp0s3 adapter in VirtualBox to Bridged Adapter
nslookup dns.localdomain.lan says ‚ÄúTimed out‚Äù	Firewall blocking DNS (port 53)	Run sudo ufw status and ensure ‚ÄúBind9‚Äù is allowed
Internet lookup fails	No forwarding configured	Check /etc/bind/named.conf.options for forwarders section
Works on VM but not Windows	Wrong DNS IP on Windows	Confirm using ipconfig /all ‚Üí ‚ÄúDNS Servers: 192.168.0.128‚Äù
